Those three methods **still exist** on `Microsoft.Maui.Controls.Application`, so your overrides will compile and work as-is.

However, MAUI also introduces more granular **`Window` lifecycle events**. You can hook them by overriding `CreateWindow` in your `App` class:

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

    window.Created  += (s, e) => { /* ~OnStart */ };
    window.Resumed  += (s, e) => { /* ~OnResume */ };
    window.Stopped  += (s, e) => { /* ~OnSleep */ };
    window.Destroying += (s, e) => { /* cleanup */ };

    return window;
}
```

**Key differences:**

| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window Event | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| `OnStart()` | `Created` | Fired once per window |
| `OnSleep()` | `Stopped` / `Deactivated` | `Deactivated` = lost focus; `Stopped` = backgrounded |
| `OnResume()` | `Resumed` / `Activated` | `Activated` = got focus; `Resumed` = foregrounded |

For **platform-specific** hooks, use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
{
#if ANDROID
    events.AddAndroid(android => android.OnStop(activity => { /* ... */ }));
#elif IOS
    events.AddiOS(ios => ios.DidEnterBackground(app => { /* ... */ }));
#endif
});
```

**TL;DR:** Your existing overrides still work. Prefer `Window` events for multi-window support and finer control.
